objkt.name: The Last Days of Fire and Steel #310

metadata.name: The Last Days of Fire and Steel #310
metadata.description:
The Last Days of Fire and Steel uses a stippling, pointillist technique to build up an image over three hundred and sixty frames of animation, pushing approximately half-a-million dots to the canvas in that time. Each point's position, size, opacity and hue is controlled by the algorithm, shaped by the manipulation and constraint of random numbers.

Five noise fields are selected, their density and influence on the final piece chosen from carefully-curated ranges. Structures, lighting, sky events and foreground structures are also generated using random values.

Sky

The main render—the overwhelming majority of the pointillist dots—can be weighted in numerous directions, lighting the sky to the left, right or perhaps centrally. Clouds are formed from the other four noise fields, which are rendered in smaller, tighter groups.

Water

The bottom half of the picture is dedicated to a body of water, usually in the same main colour as the sky. Dot-size and density are altered towards the bottom of the piece, providing a slight feel of perspective. Additionally, dimming effects are overlaid near to the centre of the piece to subtly enhance the feeling of depth.

Structures

The buildings—which include cuboids, spires, girders and domes—are shifted slightly over time to allow their edges to blur. Sometimes they are rotated slightly, sometimes the girders will feature small, pinpoint lights that activate towards the end of the render. Very rarely the landscape will be flat and featureless: all buildings gone. There's also a rare chance of a blurred foreground overlay of twisted girders, crooked fence posts or metal posts.

Sky Events

Comets, missiles, or falling satellites: whatever they are, they descend over the render, shifting slightly under the influence of gravity. Dark streaks may also traverse the sky: a seeking craft, perhaps, or something more sinister. They advance towards a central point. There is a rare chance of a meteor burst or what must be some kind of scramble: up to eight aircraft speeding to a common destination.
Stars, explosions, supernovae or distant moons illuminate the sky, sometimes as an inverted, dense point of light, other times as a halo of frosty moonglow. A rare chance of a full-spectrum rainbow star is there.

Sound

In a first for a Mandy Brigwell artwork, I've included a soundtrack for this piece. A moody, ambient layering of analogue synth and percussion can be activated by the viewer, enhancing the experience of the artwork. Sound must be activated by the user: press [I] for details.

Post-Render Effects

The render is complete after three hundred and sixty frames, but some render effects continue for a further two thousand or so frames, gently fading away to nothing. This prevents a sudden completion of the work, and is included with display in mind.

Interactivity

Press [I] for details. Double-click to go fullscreen.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #643
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Celebrations #79
metadata.description:
Celebration is a presentation of colors, patterns, and flow fields into a beautiful arrangement. The algorithm's core consists of a flow field packed with circles on top without collisions between themselves and the edges. Patterns are then drawn on top of the circles using Sayama's p5.pattern library.  I hope we take this holiday season to celebrate our little wins and successes with gratitude and enjoy what we have.

For flow field lovers, check out my study on flow fields at http://www.theflo.xyz/

objkt.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #57

metadata.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #57
metadata.description:
Julia's Magical Bulbs are 3D dimensional fractals, based on the Julia Sets of the Mandelbulb fractal.

The token is interactive, use your mouse-wheel to zoom-in and see all the little details. You will find a menu in the lower-right corner which allows you to play with the iterations and camera position. You can also render high-resolution images here.

A little bit of magic happens when you select low iteration values, perhaps your token will even default to this. 

Technical:

Not all browsers support multi-threaded modules, the fallback mode is quite slow. Try Chrome if your browser is not supported.

Calculated in full 64-bit on the CPU (not the GPU) for more accurate and detailed images.

metadata.name: Beautiful Mind #13
metadata.description:
In the logical completion of tasks, thought, order and action play a very basic, basic and sensitive role if applied in the same way.
For every operation and the most difficult tasks, these three phenomena should be used in the planning stage correctly and logically, so that the task will be completed at the right time and reach the right result.
The creative mind must determine if each of these three phenomena plays its role in the work before initiating any action, especially in basic and infrastructure works (such as social and economic planning or long-term educational and training programs).
Thinking before taking any action is one of the most fundamental underlying issues of taking any action in order to design and plan a logical and reasonable framework.
It is generally understood that thoughts, orders, and actions work together, for example, order only becomes possible when thought about a phenomenon begins, and gradually, the effects become evident.

The purpose of this code is to force minds to be creative.

metadata.name: Late Night Sketches #201
metadata.description:
This project is part of an experiment combining hand-drawn "squiggles" and turning them into something unexpected. 

The assets used in this project were hand-drawn with markers, pens, brushes, and ink. I will sit down for several hours and draw a page of elements in one of my sketchbooks. I then scan the drawings and separate them into transparent png files in Photoshop. Then the p5.js sketch takes those images and places them according to a grid. 

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: print size @ 3000px x 3000px
